\AppleTypeServicesU1 Encapsulating semantic differences requires the mediatior to have knowledge about: how agent have applied conceptualisations and representations about the DoA when formulating their data to represent the SoA; what semantic alignments exist that reconcile the semantic differences that exist between the agents that partake in a conversation; and, how data must be transcribed accordingly without introducing phantom semantics. Promoting semantic loose coupling is realised: by reducing the many-to-many conversations that exist between collaborating agents to many-to-one conversations, i.e., only between the agents and the mediator; by keeping agents from adhering to prior agreed representations. V\AppleTypeServicesU0 arying conversations independently requires the mediator to have knowledge about: the business collaborations that apply; what conversations comprise a business collaboration, and how \AppleTypeServicesU1 those conversations relate to each other\AppleTypeServicesU0 ; \AppleTypeServicesU1 what agents are partaking in a particular business conversation and what semantic meaning they contribute to or require for it.\AppleTypeServicesU0 \
